title: Origin of the word 'physics'
description: The word 'physics' originates from the Latin 'physica', meaning 'study of nature'. This Latin term is borrowed from the Greek 'phusikḗ', which means 'natural science' and is derived from 'phúsis', signifying 'origin, nature, property'.

title: Origin of Physics
description: Physics originated from ancient Greek philosophy, with early contributions from philosophers like Thales, Democritus, and Aristotle.

title: Natural Philosophy
description: Until the late 18th century, physics was known as natural philosophy.

title: Physics as a Distinct Discipline
description: By the 19th century, physics became recognized as a discipline separate from philosophy and other sciences.

title: Scientific Method
description: Physics relies on the philosophy of science and employs the scientific method, including a priori and a posteriori reasoning, as well as Bayesian inference.

title: Philosophy of Physics
description: The philosophy of physics explores issues such as the nature of space and time, determinism, and various metaphysical outlooks like empiricism, naturalism, and realism.

title: Physicists on Philosophy
description: Notable physicists like Laplace, Schrödinger, and Penrose have discussed the philosophical implications of their work.

title: Hawking's Reductionism
description: Stephen Hawking described himself as an 'unashamed reductionist' and disagreed with Penrose's Platonist views.

title: Core Theories of Physics
description: Physics includes a set of core theories that are widely used by physicists in various fields. These theories have been extensively tested and are considered adequate approximations of nature.

title: Classical Mechanics
description: The theory of classical mechanics describes the motion of objects that are significantly larger than atoms and moving at speeds much slower than the speed of light.

title: Chaos Theory
description: Chaos theory is a branch of classical mechanics that was discovered in the 20th century, despite classical mechanics itself being formulated by Newton in the 17th century.

title: Research Literacy
description: Physicists, regardless of their specialization, are expected to be knowledgeable in core theories such as classical mechanics, quantum mechanics, thermodynamics, statistical mechanics, electromagnetism, and special relativity.

title: Fall of the Western Roman Empire
description: The Western Roman Empire began losing territory around 400 AD and the last emperor abdicated in 476 AD, leading to the division of lands among various ethnic groups with often ephemeral and fluctuating rule.

title: Unifying Factors of Post-Roman Europe
description: After the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the gradual adoption of Christianity and the use of Latin in Western Europe served as unifying factors, while Greek held a similar status in the Eastern Roman Empire.

title: Late Antique Little Ice Age
description: A period of global cooling from 536 to about 660, caused by volcanic eruptions, led to dimmed skies, lower temperatures, crop failures, and famines in Europe.

title: Plague of Justinian
description: Beginning in 541 and recurring until 750, the Plague of Justinian may have killed up to 25 percent of the population in the Eastern Roman Empire and similarly in Western and Northern Europe.

title: Impact on Agriculture
description: The combined effects of climatic cooling and the plague during the 6th and 7th centuries led to reduced grain harvests and unattended vineyards, as described by John of Ephesus.

title: Population Decline in Europe
description: Europe's population was significantly lower in 600 AD compared to 500 AD, with an estimated decrease from 11 million to 8 million on the Italian peninsula, remaining at that level for nearly 300 years.

title: The Fall of the Western Roman Empire
description: The fall of the Western Roman Empire is often associated with a 'dark age' in Western Europe where knowledge, civility, and the arts were believed to have declined.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-0

title: Improvement for Farmers
description: After the fall of the Roman Empire, the majority of the population, who were farmers, may have experienced an improvement in their conditions due to reduced tax burdens, a weakened aristocracy, and greater freedom.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-1

title: Transformation of Roman Villas
description: Roman villas, once symbols of elite status and worked by slaves, were abandoned or repurposed for more practical uses following the collapse of Rome.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-2

title: Population Decline and Labor
description: The 6th-century population decline may have led to a labor shortage, which in turn facilitated greater freedom for rural people who were previously slaves or legally bound to the land.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-3

title: Agricultural History of the Eastern Roman Empire
description: In contrast to Western Europe, the Eastern Roman Empire saw an expansion of market-oriented and industrial farming, along with the adoption of new technologies like oil and wine presses during the Early Middle Ages.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-4

title: Settlement Patterns in the East
description: Unlike the villa-dominated landscapes of the West, farmers in the Eastern Roman Empire lived in villages that continued to exist and even expand during the Early Middle Ages.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-5

title: Iberian Peninsula's Unique Experience
description: The Iberian Peninsula had a distinct experience compared to the rest of Europe, with evidence of both farmland abandonment and reforestation due to depopulation, as well as expanded grazing and market-oriented livestock raising.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-6

title: Iberian Economy and North Africa
description: The economy of the Iberian Peninsula became largely disconnected from Europe and instead established itself as a major trading partner with North Africa in the fifth century.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-The Early Middle Ages-7

title: Arab Agricultural Revolution in Iberia
description: The Arab Muslim rulers introduced or popularized a large number of new crops and agricultural technology in the Iberian peninsula during the 8th through the 15th centuries.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Agriculture in Iberia-0

title: New Crops Introduced by Arabs
description: Crops such as sugar cane, rice, hard wheat (durum), citrus, cotton, and figs were introduced to the Iberian peninsula by the Arab Muslims.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Agriculture in Iberia-1

title: Advanced Agricultural Methods
description: Sophisticated methods of irrigation, water management, and agricultural technologies like crop rotation, pest management, and natural fertilization were employed for the new crops.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Agriculture in Iberia-2

title: Debate on Agricultural Innovations
description: Scholars debate whether the agricultural advancements were unique to the Arab Agricultural Revolution or a continuation and expansion of techniques from the Roman era in the Middle East.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Agriculture in Iberia-3

title: Transformation of Iberian Landscape
description: The introduction of new crops and technologies by the Arabs significantly changed the Iberian landscape starting in the 8th century.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Agriculture in Iberia-4

title: Transition from Roman to Feudal Systems
description: The Roman system of villas and agricultural estates using partly slave labor transitioned to manorialism and serfdom.

title: Characteristics of Feudal Society
description: Historian Peter Sarris identified characteristics of feudal society in sixth century Italy, Byzantine Empire, and Egypt.

title: Differences between Villa and Manor
description: Roman villas were commercially oriented and specialized in agriculture, while medieval manors aimed for self-sufficiency.

title: Decline of Slavery
description: Slavery, crucial for the Roman Empire's agricultural labor force, died out in western Europe by 1100.

title: Serfdom
description: Serfs were tied to the land with secure tenure but limited rights, owing labor or rent to their lord.

title: Feudalism's Peak
description: Feudalism was fully established in northern Europe by 1000, with its heartland in the Seine valley of France and the Thames valley of England.

title: Medieval Social Structure
description: The medieval population was divided into three groups: clergy ('those who pray'), nobility and knights ('those who fight'), and peasants ('those who work').

title: Economic and Social Dynamics
description: Peasants supported the clergy and nobility with labor and taxes in exchange for religious services and protection.

title: Decline of Central Authority
description: After the end of the Carolingian Empire, the power of kings declined, leading to a patchwork of semi-autonomous fiefdoms.

title: End of Feudalism
description: Feudalism in western Europe ended around 1500, influenced by the Black Death and subsequent labor scarcity.

title: Structure of a Manor
description: A medieval manor typically consisted of a manor house, church, village, and lands with various uses, often controlled by lords or the church.

title: Open-field System
description: The open-field system in Medieval Europe was characterized by unenclosed fields without barriers between different farmers' lands, featuring long, narrow strips of land in a ridge and furrow pattern.

title: Scattered Land Ownership
description: Farmers owned or farmed several different strips of land scattered around the farming area to reduce the risk of crop failure, as did the lord of the manor and the parish priest.

title: Communal Cooperation
description: The open-field system required cooperation among community residents, the lord, and the priest, with communal rotations and regulation of cropping.

title: Two-field Cultivation Pattern
description: A two-field cultivation pattern involved dividing arable land into two fields, with one cultivated and the other left fallow each year, rotating crops annually.

title: Three-field Cultivation Pattern
description: A three-field pattern, typical in northern Europe's wetter climate, involved rotating crops among three fields, with one planted in autumn, one in spring, and one left fallow.

title: Common Land Use
description: Common areas of wood and pasture, as well as fallowed fields, were used for communal grazing and wood-gathering, with strict management to avoid overgrazing.

title: Less-communal Variant
description: A less-communal variant of the open-field system existed in less productive agricultural areas, with more concentrated land holdings and individual or small group decision-making.

title: Enclosed Field System
description: The enclosed field system, found in pastoral and mixed farming areas, was characterized by individual decision-making and enclosed land with hedgerows, stones, or trees.

title: Farmers' Land Holdings in 1279
description: In a 1279 survey of seven English counties, 46% of farmers held less than 10 acres, insufficient to support a family. Some had no land, working for others or having additional trades. Thirty-three percent had about 12-16 acres, enough for family support. Twenty percent had about a full virgate, allowing for surplus production. A few had more than a virgate, being relatively wealthy but not noble. Thirty-two percent of arable land was owned by the lord of the manor, with farmers working or paying rent on it.

title: Important Crops of the Late Roman Empire
description: In the late Roman Empire, bread wheat was the most important crop in Italy, while barley was significant in northern Europe and the Balkans. Viticulture and olives were important near the Mediterranean Sea.

title: Introduction of Viticulture
description: The Romans introduced viticulture to more northerly areas such as Paris and the valleys of the Moselle and Rhine rivers.

title: Olive Cultivation in Medieval France
description: Olive cultivation in medieval France was traditional on the southeastern coast bordering on Italy, and large-scale cultivation in Languedoc began in the 15th century.

title: Spelt in Roman Times
description: Spelt was the most common grain grown on the upper Danube River in Swabia, Germany during Roman times and remained important in Europe throughout medieval times.

title: Crops in Northern France (8th-11th Century)
description: In northern France from the 8th to 11th century, the most important crops were rye, bread wheat, barley, and oats, in that order.

title: Dominance of Rye
description: Rye became the dominant crop on many marginal and northernmost European sites due to its winter-hardiness and tolerance of poor soils.

title: Bere in Scandinavia and England
description: Bere, a kind of barley, was grown in Scandinavia and England, especially in marginal agricultural areas in Scotland.

title: Soil Influence on Crop Planting
description: In the lowlands of the Netherlands and adjacent France, soil types influenced crop planting, with rye, oats, and barley being common on sandy soils, while wheat, including spelt, was more prevalent on loess and loamy soils.

title: Crops in Wiltshire, England (13th-14th Century)
description: In Wiltshire, England during the 13th and 14th centuries, wheat, barley, and oats were the most common crops, with legumes planted on up to 8 percent of the common fields.

title: Farmers' Gardens in Medieval England
description: In medieval England, farmers' houses typically had a small garden where they grew vegetables and fruits, and raised a pig or two and a flock of geese.

title: Importance of Livestock in Northern Europe
description: In northern Europe, livestock such as cattle, pigs, and horses were more important compared to the Mediterranean area due to the availability of fodder.

title: Livestock in the Mediterranean
description: Sheep and goats were the most important farm animals in the Mediterranean, and transhumance was a common practice due to the dry summer weather.

title: Soil Differences and Draft Animals
description: Mediterranean soils were lighter, reducing the need for oxen and horses as draft animals compared to the heavier soils in northern Europe.

title: Plowing in Northern Europe
description: Heavy northern European soils required plow teams of eight oxen, leading to cooperation among farmers who shared draft animals for plowing.

title: Transition to Horses for Plowing
description: After about 1000, horses began to be used more frequently as draft animals in place of oxen, especially by the wealthy, due to their speed despite being more expensive to maintain.

title: Pigs as a Food Source
description: In medieval England and other parts of northern Europe, pigs were the most important animals raised for meat because they were prolific and required little care.

title: Sheep and Their Products
description: Sheep were valuable for their wool, skin (used for parchment), meat, and milk, though they were less valuable in the marketplace than pigs.

title: Medieval Crop Yields
description: In the Middle Ages, the average yield for wheat in Sussex, England was 4.34 seeds produced for each seed sown, 4.01 for barley, and 2.87 for oats. By contrast, 21st-century wheat production can total 30 to 40 seeds harvested for each seed sown.

title: Average Grain Yields in Medieval England
description: From 1250 to 1450, average yields of grain crops in England were 7 to 15 bushels per acre. In poor years, yields could drop to less than 4 bushels per acre, whereas 21st-century yields can reach upwards to 60 bushels per acre.

title: Medieval Agricultural Inefficiency
description: Medieval agriculture was often criticized for its inefficiency, with communal management of land and farmers having small, scattered strips of land to cultivate. The open-field system lasted for about a thousand years and was slowly replaced from 1500 to 1800.

title: Resistance to Agricultural Change
description: The transition from the open-field system to privately owned property in the 16th century was fiercely resisted, as it led to a more competitive and capitalistic society, altering the securities and certainties of land tenure.

title: Postan Thesis on Medieval Productivity
description: The 'Postan Thesis' suggests that medieval agricultural productivity suffered due to inadequate fertilization, a shortage of pasture for farm animals, and the conversion of marginal lands into arable lands, which reduced the quantity of manure.

title: Agricultural Progress in the Low Countries
description: In the 14th and 15th centuries, the Low Countries saw agricultural progress with the near elimination of fallow land by planting cover crops and high-value crops, using intensive cultivation techniques that later spread to Norfolk, England.

title: British Agricultural Revolution
description: It was not until the 17th century that England saw widespread increases in agricultural productivity, an era known as the British Agricultural Revolution.

title: Persistence of Low Yields in Russia
description: The low level of medieval yields persisted in Russia until the 19th century, with an average yield for grain in 1850 being 600 kilograms per hectare, less than half the yield in England and the Low Countries at that time.

title: Frequency of Famines in Medieval Europe
description: Famines in Europe occurred on average every 20 years between 750 and 950, mainly due to extreme weather and climatic anomalies affecting agricultural production.

title: Transportation and Grain Prices
description: In medieval Europe, the difficulty of overland transportation caused the price of grain to double for each 50 miles it was transported, making it hard to relieve famines by importing grain.

title: Crop Failures in Winchester
description: A study of crop failures in Winchester, England from 1232 to 1349 showed that harvest failure occurred every 12 years for wheat and every 8 years for barley and oats.

title: The Little Ice Age
description: The Little Ice Age, which may have begun between 1275 and 1300, likely contributed to famines by shortening the growing season.

title: Warfare and Famine in Hungary
description: Warfare, specifically in the aftermath of the Mongol invasion, was responsible for a major famine in Hungary from 1243 to 1245, resulting in the death of 20 to 50 percent of the population.

title: The Great Famine of 1315–1317
description: The Great Famine affected 30 million people in northern Europe, with five to ten percent dying. It was caused by severe winters and rainy seasons, leading to a significant drop in crop yields and the death of draft animals.

title: Population Growth and Prosperity
description: The Great Famine of 1315–1317 came after three centuries of population growth and prosperity in Europe.

title: The Black Death vs. The Great Famine
description: Although the Black Death (1347–1352) was more lethal, the Great Famine was considered the worst natural catastrophe of the later Middle Ages.

title: Agricultural Innovation in the Middle Ages
description: The mouldboard plow and its close relative, the heavy plow, were crucial innovations in medieval agriculture, allowing for the cultivation of fertile but heavy clay soils in northern Europe.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Technological innovation-0

title: Predecessor of the Mouldboard Plow
description: Before the mouldboard plow, the ard or scratch plow was used during the Roman era and was sufficient for lighter soils.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Technological innovation-1

title: Benefits of the Mouldboard Plow
description: The mouldboard and heavy plows improved weed control, soil fertility, and field drainage through the ridge and furrow pattern they created.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Technological innovation-2

title: Impact of the Heavy Plow
description: The heavy plow contributed to increased food production, population growth, specialization of function, urbanization, and the growth of leisure in medieval Europe.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Technological innovation-3

title: Introduction of the Horse Collar and Horseshoe
description: Around 1000, the horse collar and horseshoe came into general use in Europe, enhancing the pulling capacity of horses and protecting their hooves, making horses a viable alternative to oxen.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Technological innovation-4

title: Population Growth Due to Agricultural Advances
description: Technological innovations in agriculture led to a significant population increase in Europe from 1000 to 1300, which was later impacted by the Great Famine and the Black Death.
uuid: Agriculture in the Middle Ages-Technological innovation-5

title: Scope of Plant Physiology
description: Plant physiology encompasses the study of all internal activities of plants, including chemical and physical processes at various scales of size and time.

title: Subdisciplines
description: Major subdisciplines of plant physiology include phytochemistry, which is the study of plant biochemistry, and phytopathology, which is the study of plant diseases.

title: Phytochemistry
description: Plants produce unique chemical compounds for functions such as photosynthesis, defense against herbivores, pathogens, and competition, as well as for attracting pollinators.

title: Plant Cell Characteristics
description: Plant cells have distinctive features like a cell wall and chlorophyll, which contribute to their unique behaviors compared to animal cells.

title: Cell, Tissue, and Organ Interactions
description: Plant physiology studies the specialization of cells, tissues, and organs for functions such as nutrient acquisition and transport within the plant.

title: Regulation of Internal Functions
description: Plants regulate internal functions through hormones and respond to environmental cues such as light, which affects processes like flowering and fruit ripening.

title: Environmental Physiology
description: Plant physiology includes the study of plant responses to environmental stresses, which can be influenced by genetic, chemical, and physical factors.

title: Common Chemical Elements
description: Plants are constructed from chemical elements such as carbon, oxygen, hydrogen, nitrogen, phosphorus, and sulfur, which are common to all life forms including animals, fungi, bacteria, and viruses.

title: Unique Plant Compounds
description: Plants produce a vast array of chemical compounds with unique properties to cope with their environment, including pigments for light absorption and detection, and substances used in dyes, rubber, and biofuel production.

title: Plants in Pharmacology
description: Some plant compounds have pharmacological activity and are used in medicines, such as salicylic acid for aspirin, morphine, and digoxin. Drug companies invest heavily in researching plant compounds for medicinal benefits.

title: Plant Hormones
description: Plants produce hormones and other growth regulators to signal a physiological response in their tissues.

title: Phytochrome
description: Plants produce phytochrome, a compound sensitive to light, which triggers growth or development in response to environmental signals.

title: Environmental Physiology as a Discipline
description: Environmental physiology is a subdiscipline of plant ecology that is both one of the newest and one of the oldest fields of study.

title: Synonyms of Environmental Physiology
description: Environmental physiology is also known as ecophysiology, crop ecology, horticulture, and agronomy, depending on the research perspective and goals.

title: Scope of Environmental Physiology
description: Environmental physiology involves studying how plants respond to their environment, overlapping with the field of ecology.

title: Physical Factors in Plant Response
description: Environmental physiologists study plant responses to physical factors like radiation, temperature, fire, wind, water relations, and nutrient cycling.

title: Biological Factors in Plant Response
description: The subdiscipline also examines plant responses to biological factors, including both negative interactions (competition, herbivory, disease, parasitism) and positive interactions (mutualism, pollination).

title: Plant Perception and Response
description: Plants can perceive and respond to physical stimuli and damage at a cellular level, but they do not feel pain due to the absence of pain receptors, nerves, or a brain.

title: Evolutionary Differences Between Plants and Animals
description: Unlike animals, the evolution of plants is shaped by life and death rather than by suffering, as they lack a nervous system.
